@node "MapEdit" "Map Editor     "
@{fg shine}The Map Editor@{fg text}

This is where you edit the map the world is played on.  Currently, your
starting position is (0,0), the top lefthand corner of the map, but this
will soon be rectified.

@{i}  Blocks number 0-127 are passable...the player can walk over them.
  Blocks number 128-255 are impassable...the player cannot walk over them.
  There is no support for invisible impassables yet, but I plan to add
them.
  For an example of these, play Chrono Trigger and walk behind a building.@{ui}

@{fg shine}Map--@{fg text}

This is where you can physically put blocks down and change the size of the
map.  Changing its size erases the current map, but not the icons. The
scroll bars move you around the map.

@{fg shine}BigMap--@{fg text}

For those who can't stand using Map to make their maps, BigMap allows a
larger editing area, at the expense of Width and Height gadgets, or
coordinate displays.

@{fg shine}Icons--@{fg text}

A zoomed picture of the current block.  Click on a color to select it ad
click on the big square to the left of the colors to draw.  Check out the
@{"Clipboard features" alink "Clipboard" 0} here.

@{fg shine}Palette--@{fg text}

The Map file (.CMAP) stores the palette definitions for the entire
adventure. Click on a color to select it, and use the scrollbars (Red,
Green, Blue in order) to adjust the colors.  No spreads, exchanges, or
copies (yet).

@{fg shine}Disk--@{fg text}

Save and load your .CMAP files.  Also give memory information.

  @{"Back to Main" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "ObjEdit" "Object Editor  "
@{fg shine}The Object Editor@{fg text}

This is where you create your objects in your game, both drawing and
defining object properties.

@{fg shine}ZoomDraw--@{fg text}

Same as @{"MapEdit/Icons" link "MapEdit" 0}...a zoomed up picture of the current object.  The
@{"Clipboard" alink "Clipboard" 0} is here, too.

@{fg shine}Properties--@{fg text}

This is the place to customize your objects completely.  It may take a bit
of logic to understand how it works, but its pretty powerful.

Down the window are two lists of object names.  Below that is an object
naming gadget.  After that, you can enter the object's type.  After that, a
place to choose a message type for your object's logic.  Then, two gadgets
for customizing opening and closing messages.

@{i}Now that that's been explained:@{ui}

  When you create your object, you should name it first.
  Then, right-click on those two lists.  The object names will change to
  the current object name.
  Now, here's the hard part.  Once you create a bunch of objects, you need
  to link them together in a (hopefully) logical pattern with these two
  lists.

@{i}    The list on the left are objects that this object wants.
    The list on the right are objects that it will give.@{ui}

  There are several ways these can be set, either being itself or another
  object:

@{fg fill}    OBJECT    SELF@{fg text}

      OBJECT will be added to the Want list, increasing the number of
      objects this object wants--it also flushes the Want list.

@{fg fill}    SELF    OBJECT@{fg text}

      OBJECT will be added to the Give list, and the Want list will be
      flushed.

@{fg fill}    OBJECT  OBJECT@{fg text}

      The first OBJECT is put in the Want list; the second in Give.
      Then, both lists are Flushed.

@{fg fill}    SELF      SELF@{fg text}

      The Give list is flushed.

    Probably a better way to explain this is with an example:

    You have an object named Bill.  He has the following logic:@{fg shine}

    Bill             Flute
    Bill             Sword74
    Bill             Bill
    RayGun23         Bill
    Glass of Beer    Bill
    Video Game       Cellular Phone
    AC Adapter       Scythe36W
    Bill             Bill
    Bill             Bill
    Amiga Mouse      Amiga Hard Drive@{fg text}

    Here is what will happen when you talk with Bill:

@{i}      He will give you the Flute and Sword74, if you don't already have
      them.  This will happen no matter what you have.

      If you have RayGun23, a Glass of Beer, and a Video Game, he will give
      you a Cellular Phone in exchange for those objects.

      Then, if you have an AC Adapter, he will exchange that for a
      Scythe36W.

      A few places are skipped, as Bill is a disappearing character, and
      when a character is a disappearing character and his last bit of
      logic is fulfilled...in this case, when you posses an Amiga
      Mouse and he gives you an Amiga Hard Drive...he will disappear.@{ui}

    Probably the best way to figure this stuff out is to look at an
    existing file and go from there.

