@node "ObjLct" "Object Locator "
@{fg shine}The Object Locator@{fg text}

This is where you put down characters and objects on the map.  A bit of
warning:  The Engine will slow down considerably with a lot of objects on
the map.  Keep the number you plop down to about 30 or 40--100 is the max.

@{fg shine}Map--@{fg text}

Choose an object from the top @{"(the Top Section, remember?)" link "Start" 0}.  Then, click on
the map where you want to place it.  If you want to remove all the objects
like the one at the top, right-click on the map.

@{fg shine}Save/Load--@{fg text}

Save (and load!) your .OLCT files.

  @{"Back to Main" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "ChrAnim" "Character Anim "
@{fg shine}The Character Animator@{fg text}

This is probably the final step in creating your adventure...animating the
main character.  This is the only object with animation (right now!), so get
it right!

@{fg shine}Fore, Back, Left, and Right--@{fg text}

These choose the view of the character you wish to edit.  The @{"Top Screen" link "Start" 0} bar
chooses which frame you wish to animate.

I've discovered, after staring at several of the Chrono Trigger characters,
that the animation looks more realistic if there is no "middle-frame". Leave
me to explain this concept  @{b}(WARNING!  Cheesy Ascii Grafx!)@{ub}--

    O    O   O    @{i}If you can't decipher this, there is a frame in the@{ui}
   /#-   #  \#-   @{i}middle where the character's legs and arms...at least@{ui}
   / \   |  / \   @{i}the back ones..are hidden.  This not look good!@{ui}

If you get your hands on a copy of Chrono Trigger, watch how they walk. This
should help explain it a lot better than @{b}cheese Ascii graphic@{ub}s! Especially
